        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-07-06T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-07-06T07:00:00-05:00" n="1238"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1238">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 867.48/325</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Turkey</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PH1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Philip</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-07-06T15:00:00+03:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 6, 1916, 3 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 9, 7 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1930. Your 2784, June 24, 5 p. m., received July 5. I have had several
                    conversations lately with the Minister for Foreign Affairs concerning your
                    proposal to send relief supplies to Syria and the Lebanon, and asked him
                    yesterday the question embodied in your above instruction. He again stated that
                    all his information convinces him that no famine situation exists, and that
                    owing to exceptionally good crops the supply of wheat is sufficient for the
                    population. He believes that false reports have been sent abroad by unprincipled
                    persons who expect to benefit by any help which may be sent, and that it would
                    convey a wrong impression for the Government to permit the importation and
                    distribution of relief supplies by neutrals there when other regions in Turkey
                    are equally and perhaps more in need of them. In reply to my insistent requests
                    for a prompt reply and acquiescence in the Department’s proposal, Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs said that he had fully represented the proposal to the Minister
                    of the Interior for whose decision he is now waiting. I am doing all I can to
                    obtain that desired permission.</p>
                <p>He also said that he had submitted to Minister of the Interior the draft of a
                    proposed reply to be sent to the telegram of the Turkish Chargé d’Affaires at
                    Washington on this subject.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Philip</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
